 The signal power spectrum, m}, is a strongly nonuniform function in the optical processor as described above. It is possible to eliminate the signal power term completely from the output of the optical Fourier processor. In the usual Fourier processor, which utilizes an input recording and light modulaing medium, all input data elements to be operated on coherently by the optical processor are simultaneously present in the input aperture of the processor; an input argument, 1-, is represented as a linear displacement. The variable p, conjugate to r, is proportional to the direction cosine of a diffracted plane wave. The direction cosine is evaluated for the angle between the wave normal and the direction of positive 1. It is possible to reverse the roles of displacement and angle in the processor. The input argument, 7, is made proportional to the direction cosine, a, of a scanned input plane wave. 
